That's my point.

People are bitching about zero shot AI art like it's a "problem" when it's basically the next evolution in clip art. Clip art had its place. When you saw it you knew it was something some office Karen or Stacy farted out, and that was fine. We're now in an era where clip art is better, but it's still limited. Real niggas know that No True Artsman is afraid of it because it pushes him to be more creative and do what the robots can't do yet. Pussy ass bitches who think taking fap commissions from FA users is a career path are vulnerable and rightfully so.

But there's no point in trying to separate it, just like how in music the drum machines and sampling synths went through the life cycle of "Hey this is new" to "ROBOT DESTROYS MUSIC!" to "That's not REAL music" to "It's a great tool to do better music on a budget" to today when we appreciate real orchestras when we hear them but nobody gives a shit about the technology except when people lean on them so hard that it becomes annoying (like autotune abuse or dubstep).

Zero shot AI art will always be a step behind because it will push "real" artists forward, and soon AI as finishing tools and effect filters will be so common nobody will care anymore and will go back to appreciating the quality of the final products.

It's a difference between pushing and pulling.

This is /hmofa/ so we are pulling, pulling /hmofa/ content into here. Discriminating by tool used to generate it only reduces the thread's ability to pull content, making it a smaller, weaker place.

Anonymous Sun 09 Jun 2024 23:53:27 No.66471258 Report
Quoted By:
>>66470609
Yeah, that's honestly a tricky thing when it comes to these kinds of stories. But the way I see it, it's like writing near-future sci-fi. There's a million ways you can take it, but the only things that are going to stick out as different are the things that you as a writer make important. Most sci-fi stories don't open on a 5 chapter primer on the setting, they just imply things as they go along. And that seems to be the right way to go about it: just write with a consistent, logical setting behind the scenes, and your readers will get the picture as you fill in the colors. Like, if you have a setting where anthros evolved alongside humans, it just takes little nudges. People learned about anthro biology in school, they have their own historical cultures, they're socially treated along the lines of another race, things like that.

Kids of the '80s were set up for this with the Disney animated library, Don Bluth's better films, shitloads of cartoons from the '80s & '90s, and the early niche proliferation of furry content on web 1.0 that preceded the subculture's footprint in modern pop-culture that formed the first rejections against it.
I became an instant fan of Star Fox 64 when it dropped in 1996, and fan-art/fanfiction got me looking for art similar to what Marybeth Koscinski(sp?) had made; I inevitably found FurNation very soon after; VCL after that. That led to infrequently collecting print media and eventually purchasing commissions and slowly trying to anonymously help build the culture.
So it goes.
